reviews.review_text:
The GRATEFUL DEAD "Live" November 5-8 1970 at the Capitol Theater, Port Chester, New York, U.S.A. :
:
:
I highly recommend this download for your collection. 

A "Must Have" for all collectors of 1970 GRATEFUL DEAD, which is some of the best GRATEFUL DEAD there ever was.

Here is a rare opportunity to listen in on a concert gone with the wind. 

I've learned to appreciate and respect audience recordings. The love from these shows still comes through. 

Port Chester audiences in 1970 were very respectful of the music and I think the DEAD enjoyed that. You can hear it in the music.

Listen with your heart, and ears and audience tapes can take you back to a time long forgotten. 

Count your blessings that we have this show to listen to. 39 years ago I was 15 and a fan of the GRATEFUL DEAD. Funny to call the Vietnam War days the GOOD OLD DAYS...I knew that paradox would rear its ugly head when I was 15 and here it is...but they were the good old days...compared to today, just like today will be the good old days 39 years from now. Makes you wonder if we all aren't mad.

Eat, Drink, Be Merry and Listen to the GRATEFUL DEAD. 

Thanks for the love.

The Grateful Dead This show is as Grateful Dead as it gets. I had several flashbacks listening to this and words fail to compare what it must have been like to be part of this show. All aboard we're going for a ride.

Epic, but flawed The set list is interesting. The playing is fair to awesome. The sound quality is mostly top-notch for '70, but not all of it: there are truly horrible moments for this recording. I give it 4 stars, but not easily.
not a soundboard Not a soundboard!

Great Document It just dawned on me that the first several acoustic tunes are the soundcheck.

Wow, this entire show is really something. And I, too, enjoy the historic audience recordings. It really gives the shows a special feel. Hats off to the tapers who were able to pull their magic off in this age.

The Usher speaks My wife Judy and I taped all the Capitol shows, in their entirety, for the entire time we were there.
I used a Sony TC124S recorder and Sony cardioid mics spaced about 20 feet wide along the balcony.
I had installed shielded cables along the edge of the balcony and that stayed in place for the 11 months that we were there..
Got lots of good music and it does me well that so many folks are out there enjoying the great sounds that occurred those magical nights.
Have fun, keep listening.
Ken Lee
good>great Casey Jones through Good Lovin' is the early show. Don't Ease through UJB is the late show acoustic set. Alligator on down is the late electric set and it is remarkable.

is this IT ? this show, especially the extended final sequence, may just be the high-water mark for the Dead in the primal mold, because Pigpen.

this concert deserves nothing less than a Spinal Tap "It goes to 11".

Pigpen, tell 'em 'bout the Bear! Excellent late 1970 show and an exemplary AUD for the time. Thank you Ken and Judy Lee, and others involved in improving the quality over the years. I never really got into '70 and '71 much before but have been listening a lot lately and love to hear the evolution from fire-breathing psychedelia to song-driven Americana. They really pulled out all the stops at the end with the Pig jams. Never heard the "Bear" rap before. Wonder if that was Bobby and Pig messing with Owsley.
